The <b>Black-capped Swallow</b> (<i>Notiochelidon pileata</i>) is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hirundinidae" title="Hirundinidae" class="mw-redirect">Hirundinidae</a> family. It is found in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Salvador" title="El Salvador">El Salvador</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guatemala" title="Guatemala">Guatemala</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honduras" title="Honduras">Honduras</a>, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitats</a> are subtropical or tropical moist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montane_forest" title="Montane forest" class="mw-redirect">montane forests</a> and heavily degraded former forest.
It was first described by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Gould" title="John Gould">John Gould</a> as <i>Atticora pileata</i> in the <i>Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Gould2_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gould2-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>
